questions.scenario:
You are debugging a production issue in a Spring Boot 3.2 application that has enabled Virtual Threads via `spring.threads.virtual.enabled=true`. You notice that during peak traffic, the application's throughput drops significantly and CPU utilization on the worker nodes spikes, despite the application being IO-bound. You find the following code snippet in a legacy integration module: 

java
public class LegacyDataService {
    private final Object lock = new Object();

    public void processData() {
        synchronized (lock) {
            // Performs a blocking network call to a legacy mainframe
            String response = restTemplate.getForObject("http://legacy-api/data", String.class);
            persistResponse(response);
        }
    }
}

You are investigating why a business-critical audit log is not being persisted asynchronously in a Spring-managed service. The method `createTransaction` is called by an external controller, but the `saveAuditAsync` method seems to execute on the same thread as the caller and fails to roll back when the main transaction fails. 

java
@Service
public class TradeService {

    @Transactional
    public void createTransaction(TradeData data) {
        // ... business logic ...
        saveAuditAsync(data);
    }

    @Async
    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
    public CompletableFuture<Void> saveAuditAsync(TradeData data) {
        // ... persist audit log ...
        return CompletableFuture.completedFuture(null);
    }
}

You are debugging an issue where a high-throughput data pipeline using `CompletableFuture` hangs indefinitely under heavy load. The pipeline aggregates data from multiple microservices: 

java
public CompletableFuture<UserDTO> getUserFullProfile(String userId) {
    return CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> userService.fetchBase(userId))
        .thenCompose(base -> CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
            return authService.getRoles(base.getId()); // Potentially slow IO
        }))
        .thenCombine(CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
            return prefService.getPreferences(userId); // Potentially slow IO
        }), (roles, prefs) -> buildDTO(roles, prefs));
}
